84","1540–Male":"1540–Deceased","1521–1577":"1521–1577","1583":"1583","1550":"1550","1560":"1560","1571":"1571","7 December 1578":"7 December 1578","1569":"1569","1600":"1600","1578":"1578","1577":"1577","1620":"1620","1521":"1521","1642":"1642","1575":"1575","1597":"1597","1574":"1574","April 1583":"April 1583","1585":"1585","1651":"1651","1540":"1540","1584":"1584","1559":"1559","Old Buckenham, Norfolk, England":"Old Buckenham, Norfolk, England","Norfolk, England":"Norfolk, England","All Saints' Church, Old Buckenham, Norfolk, England":"Old Buckenham, Norfolk, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Plowman","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (mainly Middlesex) and Scottish: occupational name for a plowwright or plowman, from late Middle English <i>plo(u)gh</i>, <i>plouʒ</i> ‘plow’ (Old English <i>plōg</i>, <i>plōh</i>) + <i>-man</i>."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Rebecca","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Biblical name, from the Latin form of the Hebrew name <i>Rebekah</i>, borne by the wife of Isaac, who was the mother of Esau and Jacob (Genesis 24–27). The Hebrew root occurs in the Bible only in the vocabulary word <i>marbek</i> ‘cattle stall’, and its connection with the name is doubtful. In any case, Rebecca was Aramean, and the name probably has a source in Aramaic. It has always been common as a Jewish name; in England and elsewhere it began to be used also by Christians from the 14th century onwards and especially at the time of the Reformation, when Old Testament names became popular. It was very common among the Puritans in the 17th century, and has enjoyed a tremendous vogue in England since the latter part of the 20th century, among people of many different creeds. In Scotland this is found as an Anglicized form of Beathag ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705205,"age":9,"year":"1569","julianDay":2294126,"title":"State Lottery","description":"A State Lottery was recorded in 1569. The tickets were sold at St. Paul's Cathedral in London.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705206,"age":11,"year":"1571","julianDay":2294856,"title":"The Royal Exchange is Organized","description":"The Royal Exchange was organized in January 1571 by Sir Thomas Gresham. Gresham is known as the father of English banking.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705210,"age":40,"year":"1600","julianDay":2305448,"title":"The Honourable East India Company","description":"The Honourable East India Company, a British joint-stock company, was established in 1600 for trade in the Indian Ocean region. At its height, the British East India Company had a private army which was twice the size of the British Army, ruled large sections of India, and revenues in the millions.","url":"https://www.historic-uk.com/HistoryUK/HistoryofEngland/The-East-India-Company/","urlTitle":"Historic UK - The East India Company","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705212,"age":60,"year":"1620","julianDay":2312753,"title":"The Pilgrims Board the Mayflower","description":"\"The Pilgrims boarded the Mayflower in search of religious freedom in the New World in September 1620. The Mayflower set sail from Plymouth, England, with 102 passengers, 40 of whom called themselves \"\"Saints.\"\" After two stormy months at sea, the ship reached the New World. Nearly half of the group died during their first winter due to malnutrition and the harsh New England winter.\"","url":"https://www.themayflowersociety.org/the-pilgrims/pilgrim-history","urlTitle":"The Mayflower Society - Pilgrim History","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705213,"age":82,"year":"1642","toYear":"1651","julianDay":2320789,"title":"The English Civil War","description":"A series of conflicts regarding England's governance during the years 1642 to 1651 is now known as The English Civil War. Charles I summoned supporters to join him against his enemies in Parliament. In October 1642, nearly 10,000 men fought for Charles I and chased Parliament across the River Tamar. Fighting continued for years and was finally ended at the Battle of Worcester on September 3, 1651, with a Parliamentarian victory.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Rebecca Plowman was born in 1560, in Norfolk, England, her father, Plowman, was 20 and her mother, Elizabeth Anne Lovett, was 39. She married Thomas Canne in 1574, in Old Buckenham, Norfolk, England. They were the parents of at least 3 sons and 2 daughters. She died in Old Buckenham, Norfolk, England."},"et":{"1560–":"1560–Surnud","1560–Female":"1560–Surnud","1550–1597":"1550–1597","1575–1642":"1575–1642","1578–Male":"1578–Surnud","1583–1583":"1583–1583","1585–Male":"1585–Surnud","–1584":"–1584","1540–Male":"1540–Surnud","1521–1577":"1521–1577","1583":"1583","1550":"1550","1560":"1560","1571":"1571","7 December 1578":"7. detsember 1578","1569":"1569","1600":"1600","1578":"1578","1577":"1577","1620":"1620","1521":"1521","1642":"1642","1575":"1575","1597":"1597","1574":"1574","April 1583":"aprill 1583","1585":"1585","1651":"1651","1540":"1540","1584":"1584","1559":"1559","Old Buckenham, Norfolk, England":"Old Buckenham, Norfolk, England","Norfolk, England":"Norfolk, England","All Saints' Church, Old Buckenham, Norfolk, England":"Old Buckenham, Norfolk, England"},"fi":{"1560–":"1560–Kuollut","1560–Female":"1560–Kuollut","1550–1597":"1550–1597","1575–1642":"1575–1642","1578–Male":"1578–Kuollut","1583–1583":"1583–1583","1585–Male":"1585–Kuollut","–1584":"–1584","1540–Male":"1540–Kuollut","1521–1577":"1521–1577","1583":"1583","1550":"1550","1560":"1560","1571":"1571","7 December 1578":"7. joulukuuta 1578","1569":"1569","1600":"1600","1578":"1578","1577":"1577","1620":"1620","1521":"1521","1642":"1642","1575":"1575","1597":"1597","1574":"1574","April 1583":"huhtikuu 1583","1585":"1585","1651":"1651","1540":"1540","1584":"1584","1559":"1559","Old Buckenham, Norfolk, England":"Old Buckenham, Norfolk, England"